{"\ufeffDignifying Menstruation: Why Sanitary Pads and Undergarments Are the Most Under-Donated Items in India\nPublished by CauseKind \u00b7 Women's Dignity \u00b7 June 2026\nReading time: 8 minutes\n________________\n\n\nThere is a conversation that almost never happens at donation drives.\nPeople bring bags of clothes. They bring books and school supplies. They bring old electronics and household items. They stand around and feel good about what they've brought, and volunteers sort through it all, and someone makes chai, and it is warm and purposeful and good.\nAnd somewhere in that same room, a volunteer quietly adds to a list that nobody ever talks about out loud.\nSanitary pads: zero. Undergarments: zero. Menstrual hygiene products: zero.\nNot because nobody knew. Not because people forgot.\nBecause nobody brought them.\nBecause nobody talks about them.\nBecause in India - a country of 1.4 billion people, where half the population menstruates - menstruation is still the thing we do not say at donation drives.\nThis blog is about that silence. About what it costs the girls and women who live inside it. And about how you - through your workplace, your housing society, or simply as an individual - can be part of ending it.\n________________\n\n\nThe Numbers That Should Stop Us Cold\nBefore we talk about what to do, we need to understand what is actually happening.\nAccording to research on menstrual health in India, only about 36% of women and girls in rural India have access to sanitary pads or any hygienic menstrual product. The remaining 64% use cloth rags, ash, leaves, or nothing at all - managing a natural biological process with whatever is available, however inadequate, however unsafe, however humiliating.\nIn orphanages and shelter homes - the very institutions that depend entirely on donations and government allocations - the shortage is acute and consistent. Matrons describe the same situation across different states: funds run out, NGO supply chains are irregular, and the items that come through donation drives are almost never the ones that are needed most.\nA survey of shelter homes in Maharashtra and Uttar Pradesh found that most institutions receive barely 20-30% of their monthly requirement for sanitary hygiene products through donations. The rest is either purchased from stretched operational budgets, improvised, or simply not available.\nThe girls go to school during their periods. They manage - because they have to. But they do it in discomfort, in anxiety, in the persistent low-level awareness that something basic is not being met, that their bodies are a problem nobody wants to discuss.\nThat awareness does not stay in the body. It settles in the mind. It affects how a girl moves through the world.\n________________\n\n\nWhy These Items Stay Off the Donation List\nThere is no shortage of generosity in India. There is a shortage of comfort with this particular category.\nHere is why sanitary pads and undergarments consistently fail to show up at donation drives - and why understanding those reasons is the first step to changing them:\n1. The discomfort of talking about it\nMenstruation carries decades of cultural conditioning toward silence and concealment in India. Saying \"we need sanitary pads\" in a group setting - at a workplace, at an RWA meeting, at a school - still makes people visibly uncomfortable in a way that saying \"we need school bags\" simply does not.\nThat discomfort is the problem. Not the pads. The silence.\n2. The assumption that someone else handles it\nMost donors assume that basic hygiene products are covered - by the government, by dedicated health NGOs, by the organisation's own budget. They are not. Government allocations are inconsistent. Health NGOs are stretched. Operational budgets are depleted by other essential costs first.\nThe assumption that \"someone else handles this\" is precisely why nobody does.\n3. The perception that it is too personal to donate\nUnlike books or clothes, menstrual products feel intensely personal. People worry about appropriateness - is it strange to donate this? Will it be received well?\nHere is the answer: a girl in a shelter home who receives a clean pack of sanitary pads does not think about whether the donation was appropriate. She thinks: finally.\n4. It never appears on public donation lists\nMost published donation drives list clothes, books, toys, electronics. Sanitary products rarely appear. This creates a self-reinforcing cycle - people don't see it on the list, so they don't bring it, so the matron never puts it on the list because she's embarrassed to ask, so it never appears on the list.\nBreaking the cycle requires someone to put it on the list first. Loudly. Without apology.\n________________\n\n\nWhat Girls and Women in Shelters Actually Need\nLet us be specific. Because specificity is what turns good intentions into useful donations.\nMenstrual Hygiene Products\nSanitary pads - always. The most urgently, consistently needed item. Look for:\n* Regular and overnight pads - both are needed\n* Biodegradable or cloth pad alternatives are welcome in organisations with composting or washing facilities - but confirm before donating\n* Always donate new, sealed packs. This is non-negotiable. Never donate opened or used products.\nReusable menstrual hygiene kits - where appropriate. Some forward-looking shelter homes have adopted reusable cloth pads or menstrual cups as part of sustainable hygiene programmes. Before donating these, check with the organisation - they require specific education and maintenance support to be effective.\nMenstrual pain relief: Ibuprofen and mefenamic acid tablets (commonly sold as Meftal-Spas) are among the most requested but least donated items in women's shelter homes. Dysmenorrhea - menstrual cramps - affects the majority of menstruating individuals, and for many girls in shelters, there is simply nothing available. Check with the organisation before including, but when asked for, these are genuinely impactful.\nUndergarments - New, Only New, Always New\nThis cannot be emphasised enough: undergarments must always be new and sealed.\nUsed undergarments - regardless of how clean, how good the condition - are never appropriate to donate. This is a matter of basic dignity and hygiene. There are no exceptions.\nWhat to donate:\n* Cotton underwear for women and girls - in a range of sizes (XS through XXL - larger sizes are consistently more in demand than donors realise)\n* Sports bras and regular bras in standard sizes\n* Cotton camisoles and undershirts for adolescent girls\n* Children's underwear - new and sealed, in standard sizes for girls aged 6 to 16\nA note on sizing: The most common donation mistake in this category is donating only small sizes. Women in shelter homes reflect the same natural distribution of body sizes as any population. Larger sizes are dramatically under-donated and dramatically needed. When buying for a drive, buy across the full size range - do not default to small and medium.\nGeneral Personal Hygiene\nWhile this blog focuses on menstrual and intimate hygiene specifically, organisations also consistently need:\n* Sanitary napkin disposal bags\n* Mild soap (unscented is preferred for sensitive skin)\n* Basic moisturiser - dry skin is a persistent issue in institutions with limited resources\n* Toothbrushes and fluoride toothpaste\n* Combs and hair ties\n* Mild shampoo\n________________\n\n\nThe Impact of Not Having These Things\nWe should be clear about what we are actually talking about when we talk about a shortage of menstrual hygiene products.\nA girl who menstruates without access to sanitary pads misses school.\nThis is documented across India. A study by NGO Dasra found that 23 million girls drop out of school every year due to inadequate menstrual hygiene management. They miss the first day of their period, then the second, then decide it is easier not to go at all during that week. Week after week. Year after year.\nThe absences compound. The learning gaps compound. The confidence erodes. The trajectory bends.\nA girl who had every intention of studying, of sitting exams, of moving toward a future - misses it. Not because she was not capable. Not because she did not want it.\nBecause nobody put sanitary pads on the donation list.\nThe absence of a pack of pads does not just cause discomfort. It changes the direction of a life.\nBeyond school attendance, there is the matter of infections. Cloth rags and improvised menstrual materials, when not properly washed and dried - which in crowded institutional settings is difficult - lead to bacterial infections, fungal infections, and in severe cases, reproductive health complications that follow a girl into adulthood.\nA pack of sanitary pads costs between \u20b935 and \u20b980. The cost of treating a recurrent infection is many times that - in money the shelter does not have and in suffering the girl should never have experienced.\n________________\n\n\nHow to Organise a Hygiene Product Drive\nThis is the practical heart of this blog. Here is a complete, step-by-step guide for organising a targeted hygiene product drive through your workplace or housing society - including what most organisers get wrong and how to avoid it.\n________________\n\n\nFor Corporate Employees: The Office Hygiene Drive\nStep 1 - Get senior buy-in first The single most effective thing you can do to make an office drive successful is to have a department head, HR manager, or senior leader visibly back it. Send an email, mention it at a team meeting, post on your internal communication channel. When someone senior normalises the conversation, the discomfort drops immediately and participation rises.\nStep 2 - Name it clearly and without euphemism Call it what it is: a Menstrual Hygiene and Dignity Drive. Not a \"personal care drive\" or a \"hygiene essentials collection.\" Euphemism perpetuates the problem. The name itself is an act of normalisation.\nStep 3 - Set up a collection point A clearly labelled collection box in a common area - the office kitchen, near the lift lobby, at the reception desk. Label it specifically: Sealed sanitary pads, new undergarments (all sizes), and hygiene essentials for [Name of Organisation / Shelter Home].\nStep 4 - Create a specific shopping list Most people want to contribute but do not know exactly what to buy. Remove that friction. Create a printed or digital list:\nItem\n\tSpecification\n\tSanitary pads\n\tSealed packs, regular and overnight\n\tCotton underwear\n\tNew, sealed - sizes XS to XXL\n\tSports bras\n\tNew, sealed - sizes 32 to 42\n\tIbuprofen tablets\n\tStandard 400mg strips (confirm with org first)\n\tDisposal bags\n\tFor sanitary waste\n\tMild soap\n\tUnscented bars, new\n\tToothbrushes & paste\n\tNew, sealed\n\tPost this list at the collection point and share it digitally.\nStep 5 - Set a clear timeline and end goal A two-week drive with a specific target - \"We are collecting for 50 girls at [Shelter Name] for three months' supply\" - works far better than an open-ended \"donate when you can\" approach. Specificity creates urgency and a shared sense of purpose.\nStep 6 - Partner with a verified organisation through CauseKind Do not collect items and then search for a recipient. Identify the organisation first. CauseKind connects corporate drives with verified shelter homes and orphanages that have posted specific in-kind requests. This ensures every item collected goes to a confirmed, real need - and your organisation receives a verified Impact Certificate documenting the donation.\nStep 7 - Close the loop After the donation is delivered, share a brief update with your team - a photo if the organisation consents, a summary of what was donated and who received it. This is not about recognition. It is about closing the story so colleagues feel the impact of what they participated in. It builds culture. It makes the next drive easier.\n________________\n\n\nFor Housing Societies: The RWA Hygiene Drive\nHousing societies - RWAs - are often the most natural unit for community giving in urban India. A well-organised RWA hygiene drive can collect significant quantities in a short time with relatively low coordination effort.\nStep 1 - Bring it to the RWA committee meeting Frame it as a community initiative. Most RWA committees are looking for meaningful ways to engage residents and create a sense of shared purpose. A hygiene product drive is specific, actionable, and time-bound - exactly what committees can actually execute.\nStep 2 - Use the society noticeboard and WhatsApp groups Both. The noticeboard catches the people who are not on the group. The group reaches everyone else. Keep the message short: what you are collecting, for whom, and where to drop it off.\nStep 3 - Set up tower-wise or floor-wise collection In large societies, designate a collection point per tower or per few floors - near the lift on each floor, or at the tower entrance. Reduce the distance between the item and the collection box to the smallest possible number of steps.\nStep 4 - Make it easy for residents to shop specifically Share the shopping list. Many residents will prefer to buy specific items rather than search their homes - and for hygiene products, new purchases are what is needed. A \u20b980 pack of sanitary pads and a \u20b9150 pack of new underwear - that is a \u20b9230 contribution with a real, direct impact.\nStep 5 - Coordinate delivery through CauseKind Once collected, CauseKind helps match and verify the receiving organisation, coordinates the local handoff, and issues documentation for the society's records. For housing societies that file CSR activity reports or want to maintain records of community service, this documentation matters.\n________________\n\n\nStarting the Conversation: What to Say\nIf you are the person who wants to start this in your organisation or society but are not sure how to bring it up, here is language that works:\nIn a work email: \"I'd like to propose a small but high-impact initiative for our team - a Menstrual Hygiene Drive for [a local shelter home / verified organisation through CauseKind]. Sanitary pads and new undergarments are the most urgently needed but least donated items in most Indian shelter homes. It takes very little to organise and has a direct, measurable impact. I'd love to discuss making this a quarterly team initiative.\"\nIn an RWA WhatsApp group: \"Hi everyone - I've been looking into a community initiative we could run this month. A Menstrual Hygiene Drive for [organisation name] - we'd collect sealed pads and new undergarments for girls at a local shelter home. Items can be left at the collection box near [location]. Happy to share a shopping list if it helps. Takes very little effort from each household but makes a real difference.\"\nThe key in both cases: be direct, be specific about what is needed, and give people an easy next step.\n________________\n\n\nA Final Word on Dignity\nThere is a word that sits at the centre of all of this, and it is not generosity.\nIt is dignity.\nEvery girl in a shelter home, every woman in a rural community, every resident of an orphanage - they are not asking for charity. They are asking for the basic conditions under which they can live as full human beings.\nManaging menstruation hygienically is not a luxury. It is a biological necessity. And when a girl cannot do it - because the resources are simply not there, because nobody put it on the donation list, because the silence around the subject made it easier to ignore - she carries the cost of that failure in her body, in her education, in her sense of what she is worth and what she is entitled to.\nA pack of sanitary pads says something.\nIt says: your body is not a problem. Your needs are not embarrassing. You deserve the same basics as everyone else.\nThat is the donation. The pads are just how it arrives.\n________________\n\n\nStart Here\nIf you are ready to organise a hygiene drive or make a direct in-kind donation of menstrual hygiene products through CauseKind, here is where to begin:\n* Browse verified in-kind requests from shelter homes and orphanages in your area\n* List your planned drive and connect with a verified recipient organisation\n* Receive a complete Impact Certificate for your organisation or housing society's records\nBecause the most important thing we can do right now is stop treating this as a conversation too uncomfortable to have.\n________________\n\n\nBrowse Hygiene Product Requests on CauseKind \u2192 Organise a Corporate or Society Drive \u2192 Create Your Free CauseKind Account \u2192\n________________\n\n\nCauseKind is India's verified giving platform. Zero fees. Admin-verified listings. Every donation tracked to delivery. Give with purpose.\nTo connect your corporate team or housing society with a verified recipient organisation, contact us at support@causekind.org or +91 7719938619\n________________\n\n\nTags: menstrual hygiene donation India, donate sanitary pads India, undergarment donation India, hygiene drive corporate India, RWA donation drive India, period poverty India, shelter home donation India, menstrual health India, how to organise donation drive India, CauseKind hygiene drive, women dignity donation India, orphanage donation India": null}